defaultAppendix Adefault&#xa0;
defaultCase study: Donald and Enid defaultWinterbottomdefault&#xa0;
defaultDonald and Enid 
defaultWinterbottom
default, aged 81 and 79 respectively, w
defaultere injured on 12 January 2012 when a car overtaking from the opposite direction hit their car head-on. 
defaultMrs
default 
defaultWinterbottom
default was airlifted to hospital with a severe whiplash injury. The next day while 
defaultEnid
default was still in hospital, and with no discussion with her
default, their legal expense insurers, 
defaultCogents
default, started a claim. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe medical ‘expert’ appointed by 
defaultCogents
default estimated that both Donald and Enid would recover from their injuries within 
defaultseven
default months and the company estimated damages for 
defaultMrs
default 
defaultWinterbottom
default at £1,800
default – £2,000.
default&#xa0;
defaultDonald and Enid rejected the offer and moved their claim to 
defaultMr
default 
defaultWinterbottom’s
default old union, Unite Legal Services, in November 2012. In July 2013 Thompsons Solicitors settled 
defaultMrs
default 
defaultWinterbottom’s
default case for £8,000, four times the estimated damages. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe lawyer at Thompsons who ran the case, Hazel Webb, found that 
defaultCogents
default had failed to take proper instructions from the 
defaultWinterbottoms
default and referred them to the wrong type of medical expert who missed the long-term impact of one of 
defaultMrs
default 
defaultWinterbottom’s
default injuri
defaultes – namely, numbness in her hand which needed an 
defaultorthopaedic
default specialist to whom Thompsons referred her.
default&#xa0;
defaultEnid 
defaultWinterbottom
default said
default:
default 
default“We didn’t ask for Cogent and we can only assume they got our details from our car insurance company. We were in shock after t
defaulthe accident yet we were harassed with phone calls from 
defaultCogents
default pushing us to make a claim and then, when we agreed, the way we were dealt with was so impersonal we felt like we were just a statistic
default.
default Their letters were in legal mumbo jumbo
default,
default and we struggle
defaultd to make sense of t
defaulthem
default. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default“The disinterest of the doctor they appointed was shocking. He was clearly just there to tick boxes. I had an imprint of the seat belt across my stomach and the doctor didn’t even look at it. 
default&#xa0;
default“
defaultIn the end they only offered us 
default£1,800. For all the trauma of the accident and the knock-on effect it had on our lives, it just seemed far too low. 
default&#xa0;
default“It was at this point we saw a Unite leaflet which said we could pursue a claim with them because Donald had been a member when he was wor
defaultking as an engineer. Immediately we felt a relief because a solicitor from Thompsons came to see us in our h
defaultome. 
defaultWith no children it was such a relief to know and feel that our case was being handled correctly. 
default&#xa0;
default“The accident made us 
defaultrealise
default we are not as
default invincible as we once thought we were. It’s been a very traumatic period in our lives, especially as the accident wasn’t our fault. Our confidence completely collapsed, and it is only in past few months that we have started to feel like we are on the way 
defaultto recovery. 
default&#xa0;
default“
defaultWhat happened to us is a real warning to others – don’t allow yourself to be pushed into having your insurers appoint people to act for you and get a second opinion if you are in any doubt.”
